  "text": "We claim that f (V ) ⊂ C \\ f (∂V ). On the contrary, let z ∈ V ∩ K f such that f (z) ∈ f (∂V ). If z ∈ U , a Fatou component, denote by c the center of U . Since ∂V ∩ K f consists of internal rays and z ∈ V , then, if z = c, the entire U is contained in V ; otherwise, there is a unique internal ray of U passing through z, which is contained Figure 5 . The decomposition of [z, w] and its image in [CITATION_1] in V ∪ {c}. Anyway, we can pick an internal ray r z of U with r z ⊂ V ∪ {c}. So, by choosing the landing point of r z if necessary, we can assume z ∈ J f . In this case, there is an external ray contained in f (∂V ) landing at f (z), and its lift based at z is also an external ray. As z ∈ V , all external rays landing at z belong to V ∩ U (∞). It contradicts to the fact that f (V ∩ U (∞)) = U (∞) \\ f (∂V ). The claim is then proven. Now, we fix a point w W ∈ U (∞) in each component W of C \\ f (∂V ) and denote by z W the unique preimage of w W in V ∩ U (∞). Given any connected component W of C \\ f (∂V ), and any point w ∈ W , we pick an arc γ w ⊂ W joining w and w W . We assert that γ w has a unique lift in V starting from z W . Firstly, let Γ denote the component of f −1 (γ w ) that contains z W . Then Γ ⊂ V since z W ∈ V and γ w ∩ f (∂V ) = ∅. Note also that V contains no critical points of f , so f : Γ → γ w is a covering, and hence a homeomorphism. We denote by h(w) the end point of this lift. Since W is simplyconnected, the point h(w) is independent on the choice of γ w . We then get a map h : C \\ f (∂V ) → V . This map is easily checked to be the inverse of f : V → C \\ f (∂V ). (3) Let z, w be two distinct points in V ∩ K f with f (z) = f (w). We first claim that both z and w belong to ∂V . Otherwise we can find two points z and w in V near z and w, respectively, such that f (z ) = f (w ) and this contradicts assentation (2). Assume now that z, w ∈ ∂V and let [z, w] be the regulated arc joining z, w. Figure 5 ). For each i ∈ {1, . . . , m}, set E i := f (A i ). According to (3), we get that E i = [f (z i ), f (w i )] and their interior are pairwise disjoint. We also set F i := f (B i ), i ∈ {1, . . . , m}. Clearly, each F i is a tree or point containing f (w i ) and f (z i+1 ) (see the right one in Figure 5) .",
